description.text: Customizable filament guide designed for the Prusa i3 Berlin with aluminum frame. I designed the guide so I could use a loose filament spool (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:39564) mounted behind the solid metal frame. The frame width is adjustable, so it should work with other frames. You can specify where the guide opening should be relative to your frame and the arm length and angle will be automatically calculated.

The design is adjustable for the width of your frame. For the nominal 6mm thickness of the Prusa i3 Berlin 6mm made a nice firm grip (printing at 0.3mm layer thickness, 0.6mm shell, 20% infill, 0.4mm nozzle). Measure the distance from the frame to where you want the filament guide opening to be and plug those into the x and y distances in the customizer. The OpenSCAD code will automatically determine the necessary arm length and angle. You can make a version for a spool on the left or right side of the frame (this puts the arm away from the spool so the frame grip braces better - I found that with a loose grip the guide wants to fall towards the spool). You may want to print another guide so that the filament stays off the edge of the frame (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:117720)

title: Vertical Hopper Chute Remix for the Filastruder v2.0

description.text:
I redesign the chute used on the Vertical hopper so it can be used on the Version 2.0 filastruder.

Plus I also design a vibration mechanism for the chute to solve feed issues, the vibrator is a little too powerful so I need to seal the desiccant hole up with tape otherwise it shakes the pellets out.

These are the parts needed for the vibrator you can get them from Jaycar if you live in Australia.

https://www.jaycar.com.au/standard-high-power-d-c-motors-20000-rpm/p/YM2772 12V DC motor

https://www.jaycar.com.au/timer-progr-interval-module-12v/p/AA0378 Timer module, (a relay is needed as the timer can only handle 5Amps but a 30A horn relay will work for the switching as the motor has a high current draw)

https://www.jaycar.com.au/automotive-fused-relay-spst-30a/p/SY4077 The horn relay to drive the motor.

You will need to use a 12V supply that can provide approx 14A as this is what the motor needs, (I kinda made the vibration mechanism a tad too powerful)

description.text:
Sing along..."And did those feet in ancient times...". Here is one of those dark satanic mills (or factory) that provided work for the masses in Victorian times. Hard work in dark, grim, unsafe surroundings for little pay, or as the owners would call it - a holiday camp for the lower classes.
This is a modular building, so that you can design your own victorian industrial paradise for the oppressed masses of London's East End.
I made this and the rest of the range of 28mm buildings to accompany the "In Her Majesty's Name" set of wargaming rules by Craig Cartmell and Charles Murton, published by Osprey Wargames, and because I've been watching "Ripper Street" on that new-fangled television apparatus. They should suit any variety of Victorian building usage that needs a taste of the old East End, and many of the buildings will still be alive and kicking in 'Station Roads' up and down the country and so useful for train scenery building.

Note: This series of models does not condone murder, violence or other mayhem, and sightings of the Ripper should be reported to the Metropolitan Constabulary at Great Scotland Yard preferably via telephonic device on Whitehall 1212

Design

This design is culled from contemporary photos and a spot of help from Assassin's Creed victorian offering (Can't remember the name - Syndicate?). I've tried to make it as generic and modular as possible so that any number of designs can be produced and I would love to see any makes. I've tried to add build notes into the .jpg / .pngs. Please let me know if you hit a problem I haven't foreseen.
I've added several lengths of guttering which should cover most eventualities - if not, grab a hacksaw!
Most of the buildings in this range have filled-in windows because they had no interior. description.text:

Here are re-inforced double blower holders for :

  • Single extruder
  • Chimera dual hotends

As well as those BLTouch support :

  • Below the carriage, embedded screw heads (not recommended)
  • Below the carriage, embedded nuts (allows maintenant without removing the wheels)
  • Attached on the 30mm fan, bout out of the air flow.

If you're looking for a fast and easy way to attach the BLTouch on a dual extruder head, the small corner piece is the way to go, an other alternative is this one : https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2396504

This version has modified ducts, that prevent from melting on the hotends, and a reinforced front bar with a hole for the fan.

I've also provided a single extruder version

BLTouch is attached using the spacer bar, that replaces the 5mm wheel spacers.
I've (roughly) remixed this one https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2010315 no to require to remove the nearly 20 wires that go through the X carriage plate.

EDIT: A new version that embeds the nuts rather than the screw heads is preferred, as it won't require to disassemble the X-Carriage again if you have to remove the BLTouch for maintenance.

If you intend to print ABS, print the dual duct in ABS or it will get soft and bend onto your print due to the 100°C bed.

description.text:
I wanted 3 or 4 lamps like this and never found what i wanted except for 150€/piece.
So i decided i could make one myself using PVC pipes & my 3D printer.
Plus, this lamp will drain a lot less power as it will be using LED bulbs instead of halogen.

Some pieces are required :

  • A 20€ "amazon basics" tripod
  • A 100mm piece of pvc connection tubing.
  • A 100mm PVC end cap of whatever this is called, in which you'll drill a hole for a bulb socket
  • A light socket that can fit a 14W LED bulb (1400 lumens)
  • 3 meters of electric wire
  • A pedal switch
  • A plug
  • 4x45mm screws (i chose hooks cause if found it looks better), with 4mm butterfly nuts
  • A 100m to 32mm with 90° angle piece to serve as a lamp support (don't know what it's called)
  • A cheap white plastic shower curtain (2.5€ at my local store)

23 Sep 2017: Removed the included soft box for more power and painted it red & black. I'll probably design a removable filter. I noticed rubbing PVC with acetone makes a nice surface where paint can stick quite well

19 Sep 2017: Errare humanum est... Made a mistake on the reflector. Made a new one that fits my sockets. It's 58mm at the base, some might not work (the white one i had on the prototype doesn't fit). Painted it with silver paint, came out better than i expected.

18 Sep 2017: Added an experimental reflector. Got to paint the inside with chrome paint to reduce light loss inside the lamp. Should be tilted 90° and printed with vase mode

16 Sep. 2017: Added the final mount for "Amazon Basics" tripod. Published a video : https://youtu.be/qeah2XvYVe0

12 Sep. 2017: Added a picture of the PVC parts needed

10 Sep. 2017: Glued a white plastic shower curtain to the PVC pipe with super glue & then glued the front piece on top. Lovely :) I added a pedal switch, too.
I tried to put a switch directly on the back piece but there's not enough room. Added a second tripod mount, most esthetically pleasing.

8 Sep. 2017: I added a tripod mount quick release adapter for an old piece of junk i already had, i'll probably draw some more when i get some other tripods with different mounts. I'll go for the cheap ones anyway.

This is a work in progress, some adjustments are required, a moving support is needed & some painting, too (red and black, probably).

description.text:
This is a stem mount for Garmin Edge devices.

I designed this item especially for my Garmin Edge 520 but as my researches show the lock mechanism is basically the same for all Edge devices.

... took me 13 iterations for the insert to give it a quite good "clicky" feel (but still I am not totally satisfied yet, so thing might be updated in the future).

UPDATE v2; 05/09/17
After some test-mounting and riding I wasn't satisfied at all, neither with the top cap nor with the insert. The top cap showed deformation due to the tightening torque of the screw which lead to a poor fit of the insert, caused by my design approach to make it as small and thin as possible. The insert lost it's clicky feel quite fast due to the abrasion of the noses which hold the garmin in place.

So I did a re-design. The top cap has now a increased diameter and wall thickness, risk of derformation is now minimised. The insert got two additional noses which fit into the half-rounded cutout at the garmin. Clicky feel could be improved a whole through this step.

If you have any comments or suggestions, let me know and share your makes!

Introduction Theodorus Spiral, is a geometrical structure constructed with contiguous right angle triangles. You can find some goog information on wikipedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spiral_of_Theodorus

Using in Class The class should start with the problem of building a structure with contiguos right angle triangle, What are the sides? how about te angles? Then you should note that it was Theodorus of Cyrene who came up with this. You can also talk about rational and how pitagoreans dealt with non-integer numbres. Them give them the challenge to build a spiral sataircase, a stadium, and other type of structures combining these triangles

description.text:
Unprinted/untested Design! This is intended to hold two rechargable AA batteries. Which way you place them indicates whether or not the battery is charged, as displayed by the graphic on the front. OpenSCAD file included that can be configured to any battery size.
I have a box full of loose rechargable batteries. I never know which are charged and which are not, so I'm hoping printing out a few of these holders will end that problem.

I have not printed this out as I'm still waiting for my Solidoodle2. There are two areas of concern for anyone wanting to try this print... 1) The small tongues that hold batteries of diameter 13.5mm to 14.5mm might not work as intended.
2) The empty/full icon on the front might not print correctly. The depth of the icon may need to be altered so it can print without support. If you decide to try this out I'd appreciate it if you'd post success or failure below. Any improvement tips are welcome. I've included the 123d file so you can use Autodesk 123D to tweak if necessary. UPDATE: Tue, June 19th, 2012... I've also included an OpenSCAD file (AABatteryHolder_v4.scad) with a few parameters that you can configure. As you can configure the battery diameter and tongue size, you should be able to print a version for any size cylindrical battery (or cylindrical thing). AABatteryHolder_v4.stl is the stl output of the scad file for AA batteries. Descriptions of the parameters you can change are contained within the comments in the OpenSCAD file itself. If you manage to get a working print for any size battery, please provide your parameters in the comments below. Thank you! UPDATE: Thurs 9th Aug, 2012... I've uploaded AABatteryHolder_vHoffman.stl with specific alterations for afhoffman. The diameter has been scaled up for his printer and his specific battery width. The tongue intrusion and width has been reduced to hopefully encourage flex in the PLA.

The nuts are inserted with the points upward. See pic for referrence.

List of Changes

  • The Fang - The arms were brought in so the Fang can be mounted with the 40mm fan on the outside. This helps bring in the weight of the radial fan closer to the rotational axis (hotend) and decrease the rotational momentum. Also I thickened the 40mm fan mount flange and shrunk the screw holes to 3mm. This will allow you to screw the fan onto the flange before mounting to the 40mm fan shroud... makes for a much easier mounting than trying to align 3 parts and screw them together. Also the thickness helps with durability. There is also the blend file included if you want to print a version with the sensor mounts.
  • 40mm Fan Shroud - Added a stay on screw that will help keep the shroud, fang, and fan combo in place. This requires a short 2.5mm screw. I'm using a harddrive mounting screw for the PC. Also gave the hotend clamping area a bit of flex so it's less likely to crack when putting on.
  • Removeable Hotend Mount and Clamp - Just a simple way to make the hotend mount replaceable instead of having to take apart the printer to remove the whole X Carriage.
  • X Carriage - Converted it to a removeable mounting system. You can expand on this and make your own mounts for whatever you want.. like a pen mount for drawing, maybe even a laser? That would be cool.

UPDATES

  • 20170904 - Added a hole on the hotend mount to make it easier to push out the supports in the nut slot.
  • 20170926 - Added v2 of the fang with airflow angled more toward the nozzle.

description.text:
I was disappointed with the other offerings for the A-180. So, I built one with 3D printing in mind and a working trigger! To improve on its aesthetics, I wanted to have a few parts to assemble after printing. It should be obvious where the pieces go based on their names. I have included a few extra files to provide added flexibility. I included a split as well as a complete version of the the gun body. I did this to allow you to print the body all at once (i f you are a brave soul with a good printer). Similarly, I included knurled and smooth handgrip models. You only need one pair. I found that the knurling pattern is very difficult for most printers and the 3D printing process will leave a pattern of its own. However, if you have to have knurling for authenticity, I included the knurled models. In the screen shot you will see many screws. These screws are actual screws you buy and screw into the model to make it look better. I found some interesting looking screws at Lowes. The blaster is primarily held together with E6000 glue. I robbed a spring from a ball point pen to put behind the trigger. If you don't care about that, just glue the trigger in instead.

I would say that this is a moderately difficult print and build. If you like this model, please hit like and leave comments.

Sample Lesson Plan Introduce what a star is and how it produces light in the sky. Stars are essentially balls of fire. Our sun is the closest star. At great distances stars are faint with some so dim they cannot be seen without a telescope to magnify the light. Magnitude is the term used for the brightness of a star. Note how people have seen patterns in random positions of the stars throughout history. Astronomers refer to each pattern or group of stars in the sky as a constellation. There are 88 modern constellations as described by the International Astronomical Union. Hand out the star coins. Note that each point on the disk is a star. The diameter represents the star's magnitude (brightness). Lines between the stars make connections that relate to the name given to that constellation. Explain the story behind each constellation. This is a beadlock rim for the outside of the wheel on a standard HPI Baja 5B SS 1/5 scale RC car.

The screw holes have 1 layer of support material. Be sure to drill it out before installing. 
When you install this on your Baja, be sure to clean any dirt out from between the rubber tire and the wheel. Also clean any dirt on the outside of the tire near the beadlock. Then press the notches of rubber on the tire into the rectangular slots on the wheel. Make sure all sides are pressed in nice and tight. Then press the beadlock rim on top, and while you press it down, screw in the screws. I usually screw the opposite sides until there are 4 corners then I screw in the rest of the screws lightly. Once all screws are in position, tighten them all a little bit more. Tight enough so they won't fall out but not so tight that you strip the threads in the wheel.
This will probably work on the 5B and the 5T. It will work on the rear and front wheel and it certainly will not work on the inside rim. I'll be designing an inside rim one of these days. Keep in mind it was designed for the rear wheel so it sticks out a little on the front wheel. I may do a second version for the front wheel one day.
I hope it holds up and enjoy! Perhaps one day the entire Baja will be on Thingiverse!

title: Anet A3 Vortex Ring Fan Duct

description.text:
Design for the Anet A3 metal frame for a new fan duct. The ring dose not blow the air directly at the nozzle but in a swirling vortex around and below the nozzle. This helps to keep the nozzle form being cooled by the part cooling fan. This also bolts into place, so you may need longer screws to secure it in place, or cut off the mounting tab and glue it into the fan itself. I also had readjusted my nozzle to sit a bit higher to shorten the distance between the extruder and top of the heatbreak.

Though right now I am running mine as a Bowden feed with a MicroSwiss mk8 all metal hotend.

The duct tucks nicely up into the frame of the print carriage, but still leaves room for a small strip of LED lights to shine through. It also is centered on the nozzle unlike most other ducts I have seen. No, the outlet of the fan is not centered on the nozzle, so I took some time to make sure it was as centered as possible.

The HB variant adds a small cooling duct aimed at the heatbreak.

title: Reuleaux polygons (wheels, sewer lids, coins, etc.)

description.text:
Build working non-circular wheels with Reuleaux polygons. Make "safe" sewer hole covers. Print your own British 20 and 50 pence pieces! Recall the smarty pants question about what shapes can be used for sewer hole covers? Circles and what else? You want a shape that has constant width: you don't want it to have an orientation at which it presents a narrower width and thus can pass through the opening it is covering. Well, one of the classes of shapes which work for sewer hole covers is Reuleaux polygons. Reuleaux polygons are also used for coins such as the British 20 and 50 pence, Mauritian 10 rupee, and Jordanian quarter and half dinars. For further information, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curve_of_constant_width
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reuleaux_triangle P.S. I was prompted to post this when I saw the recent 5 Shekel coin posted, Thing #25051. While that coin is not a Reuleaux polygon owing to the even number of sides (nor does it claim to be), it reminded me of the coins which are. P.P.S The rotor in a Wankel engine is not a Reuleaux triangle. Don't know why some Things which claim to be Wankel's are also tagged as Reuleaux. The sides of a Wankel are a little flatter which gives a little more volume for intake. (The shape of the sides of a Wankel are optimized for combustion ratio, not for being a constant width curve.)

Download the reuleaux.scad program and use it for your own OpenSCAD programs.
The reuleaux_polygon(n,w) module generates a Reuleaux polygon with n vertices and of constant width w centered at (0,0) in the XY-plane.  The value of n must be a positive, odd integer >= 3.

description.text:
These parts are for expanding standard M4 nylock nuts to fit the nut traps of the MPCNC. They make MPCNC assembly much more comfortable when using M4 hardware. Designed for the nut traps on the 25mm edition of MPCNC, but I expect they will fit all 3 MPCNC variants. Fusion 360 files are provided, in case you have to adjust the files to fit your particular M4 nuts.

Two types of nut expander are provided:

  • The normal nut expander. This is for general use when building an MPCNC. You will need about 30 of these, maybe more.
  • The "Short" nut expander is for use in the Roller and RollerM MPCNC-parts. The slots for nuts in these parts are pretty short, so I designed a shorter (and slightly weaker) nut expander to use here. You will need to print 8 of these.
    Warning: The short nut expanders fit very tightly in the space on the Roller and RollerM parts. You might have to gently hammer them in. Once you have hammered them in, you probably will not be able to remove the nuts from the Roller parts.

Thanks to mbef for the original idea. I tried his nut encasements, but they turned out too thin when I printed them with my 0.4mm nozzle.

The Y-axis belts on my Replicator* have always been a bit floppy, and attempting to tighten them a notch always seemed to skew the carriage and make them drum tight. The original source Thing:30708 seemed like a good idea. There were a couple of issues that needed to be fixed up though. First, I try to never leave a free nut that has to be placed and tightened blindly - a printed-in nut holder is always the way to go. Secondly, you would have to carefully measure and drill the holes to ensure the thing is correctly aligned with the belt. This was solved by making it clip over the edge of the top plate, so that the edge of the plate automatically aligns it properly. Then only one mounting screw is required. Also, the clip itself is the drill guide - you can't miss.

The clip is symmetric so you can just print two of the same for the left and right belts on the Replicator. This should work for Replicator clones too, though I think many of them only use one belt.

It could be reworked to place it closer to the drive pully, but it seems fine where it is. Also you may need to alter the OpenSCAD file if your top plate thickness is significantly different from 6mm.

*(Yes Replicator, not Replicator 1, or Original Replicator, but Replicator, period. If MakerBot marketing geniuses wanted to create confusion by also naming a later model 'Replicator' that's a problem of their making, and I don't have to cater to it.)

Yeah, I printed it so that there is a bunch of support between the top and bottom of the clip. It comes out easily enough though.

It'll need an M3 nut placed in the holder, and an M3-16 bolt to mount the clip. An M3-25 or 30 is needed for the idler axle.

The dimensions of the original thing looked like a good fit, so I imported it's stl into OpenSCAD and designed over it. I placed my objects to match the original principal features. I do this often when I want to alter a thing that doesn't provide the CAD source.

description.text: Owl Cave symbol

This is a quick and easy weekend project. I created this just as a cool decoration for the wall yet at the same time it can be used as a game of trashketball.

Materials list:

  • 3D printer
  • Laser cutter
  • String
  • Super Glue
  • Ruler
  • Level
  • Command Strips

The basketball backboard measures 24 x 14 inches.
The basketball hoop is 6 inches in diameter.

Remixed mini basketball hoop by daGHIZmo:
https://www.thingiverse.com/daGHIZmo/about
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:582302

1. Prepare your printer for the basketball hoop (Make sure that your printer has a large enough print volume first). Load the Basketball_Hoop.stl file in your slicer and print.
  2. As that is going, open up the Basketball_Backboard.dxf file in Adobe Illustrator and use a laser cutter to cut out the basketball backboard. Use more power on the border of the backboard to cut it out and use less power to engrave the square.
  3. Once, the cut is complete, use a wood stain and some masking tape to give some color to the backboard.
  4. To start the basketball hoop net, first cut out 7 strings to approximately 2ft in length.
  5. Burn the tips of the strings with a stove flame to prevent the string from splitting.
  6. Fold one piece of string evenly down the middle and feed it through the holes on the hoop.
  7. Tie two lengths of string together every 1 inch. As you get closer to the bottom of the string, tie each string closer together.
  8. Then cut the excess string once you are happy with the length of the net.
  9. Position the basketball hoop to the center of the backboard (Use a ruler to measure the distance from the left and right edges)
  10. Apply a couple drops of super glue to the back side of the basketball hoop and press the hoop against the backboard.
  11. Use command strips to hang the basketball backboard to the wall (Make sure that it is level)

You can watch a part of this video to see how to tie the net: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ONNCHOdDvMc&feature=youtu.be&t=6m54s

Printing tips
1-As with most of my models, no supports are required.

2-Be sure to clean any first layer squish if you have any problem joining parts. The parts should fit nicely when printed cleanly or with a slight first layer squish.

3-I did not require any rafts or brims for any of the parts.

..
Assembly tips:
1-The eyebrows are small and print well but if for some reason you have an issue inserting them into the head (over-extrusion or a squish that cannot be cleaned) simply flip them over and put them in with the flat side facing out.

2-The left/right eyes are interchangeable. There is an up/down positioning of each eye. If it does not look right when inserted just rotate the eye piece for a better fit.

3-The left/right shoulders look similar but are slightly different, so take care when connecting them to the dress.

4-The leg holes in the dress should be positioned toward the back.

5-The left/right shoe parts are not interchangeable but are easy to distinguish which is left and right.

5-Refer to the assembly diagram for putting the model together. The model is meant to be glued.

description.text:
Needed a mount for my GoPro session that would fit my Thor 210 quad and till allow the VTX to install on the top plate, should fit any quad-copter with 25mm standoff spacing.

23 degree tilt

Printer:

Omega i3

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

100

Notes:

See Cura screen shot

Lego + Hulk = LEGO HULK !!! Total print time was ~13 hours, and overall it came out great! The print requires supports for the arms, which I super glued to the body. Timelapse of print, plus bed removal, support removal, super glue.

Watch a timelapse video of the print!
https://youtu.be/EuTI86pGNY0

3D Print Settings:
Layer Height = 0.30mm
Print Speed = 50 mm/s
Nozzle Temp = 180 deg C
Bed Temp = 60 deg C
Fill Density = 10%
